hands_on_practices.solution:
We have a thin rod of length $L$ with uniform linear charge density 
$$
\lambda = \frac{Q}{L}
$$
placed along the $z$-axis from $z=-\tfrac L2$ to $z=+\tfrac L2$.  The quadrupole tensor is
$$
Q_{ij}=\int \rho(\mathbf r')(3x_i'x_j'-|\mathbf r'|^2\delta_{ij})\,dV
\;\longrightarrow\;
\int_{-L/2}^{L/2}\lambda\,(3x_i'x_j'-r'^2\delta_{ij})\,dz'.
$$

1.  Compute $Q_{zz}$:
$$
Q_{zz}
=\int_{-L/2}^{L/2}\lambda\bigl(3z'^2 - z'^2\bigr)\,dz'
=2\lambda\int_{-L/2}^{L/2}z'^2\,dz'
=2\lambda\cdot\frac{2(L/2)^3}{3}
=\lambda\frac{L^3}{6}
=\frac{Q\,L^2}{6}.
$$

2.  Compute $Q_{xx}$ (identical to $Q_{yy}$ by symmetry):
$$
Q_{xx}
=\int_{-L/2}^{L/2}\lambda\bigl(3\cdot0 - z'^2\bigr)\,dz'
=-\lambda\int_{-L/2}^{L/2}z'^2\,dz'
=-\lambda\frac{2(L/2)^3}{3}
=-\lambda\frac{L^3}{12}
=-\frac{Q\,L^2}{12}.
$$

3.  Form the ratio:
$$
\frac{Q_{zz}}{Q_{xx}}
=\frac{\tfrac{Q\,L^2}{6}}{-\tfrac{Q\,L^2}{12}}
=\frac{1/6}{-1/12}
=-2.
$$
